[{"id":"VH979027","type":"mcq","stimulusHtml":"<div><include href=\"../Passage/VH979015.qti.xml\" xmlns:xi=\"http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude\"></include></div><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">Which of the following activities would most likely account for the levels of indoor air pollution in India and sub-Saharan Africa, as shown in the graph?</p>\n","rubricRef":"VH979027_rubric","features":[{"type":"sharedpassage","html":"<div class=\"stimulus_reference\" xmlns=\"http://www.imsglobal.org/xsd/apip/apipv1p0/qtiitem/imsqti_v2p2\" xmlns:xsi=\"http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance\">\n<div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure presents a bar graph titled Air Pollution by Region. The horizontal axis contains the categories: India, Sub-Saharan Africa, China, Asia and Pacific Islands, Middle East and North Africa, Latin America, and Industrialized countries. The vertical axis is labeled, Percent Contribution to Local Health Risks, and the numbers 0 through 6, in increments of 1, are indicated. A key shows that two categories of data are included in the bar graph: disease instances linked to indoor air pollution and disease instances linked to urban outdoor air pollution. The data represented in the bar graph are as follows. Note that all values are approximate. India: 5.5% indoor air, 2% outdoor air. Sub-Saharan Africa: 4.9% indoor air, 1% outdoor air. China: 4.5% indoor air, 4.4% outdoor. Asia and Pacific Islands: 3.5% indoor air, 2% outdoor air. Middle East and North Africa: 3.5% indoor air, 1% outdoor air. Latin America: 0.9% indoor air, 3% outdoor air. Industrialized countries: 0.1% indoor air, 1% outdoor air.\" height=\"251\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/VH979015.g02.png\" width=\"565\" /></div>\n\n<div class=\"passage\">\n<div class=\"prose style:1\">\n<p class=\"passage_para\">Scientists have observed that the health of people living in moderately developed regions, which have developed transportation and industry but lack environmental control measures, is more likely to be affected by urban outdoor pollution than by indoor air pollution.</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n"}],"choicesHtml":["<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">Construction of homes with more efficient insulation and increased ventilation</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">Use of biomass fuel sources such as wood and charcoal for cooking</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">Industrial power plants burning fossil fuels for electrical energy generation</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">Use of chemical pesticides on croplands</p>"],"answer":1}]